data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 10 (.NET 10), the Cosmos DB provider **deprecated** the sync-over-async opt-in (e.g., `EnableSynchronousOperations`). In EF Core 11, **that opt-in is removed entirely**.

Every synchronous LINQ call against the Cosmos provider — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime with no way to re-enable the old behavior.

## How to fix it

Convert all sync calls to their async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods gain `async` modifier and `Async` suffix
- All LINQ terminal operators use `*Async()` variants from `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore`
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call stack)

> **Note:** `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory. The actual I/O happens in `SaveChangesAsync()`.
